  "text": "Next we move to the 2-D case. For a given {T h }, we will use a dual mesh {T h * } consisting of covolumes as in Chou and Vassilevski [CITATION_1] . Covolumes are obtained by adding a point to an old element in {T h } and connect it with the vertices of the element. The covolumes around an edge or associated with the midpoint of the edge is shown in Figure 1 (see diamond ST V U associated with x i ). Note that a covolume is obtained by connecting vertices with an added point, which could be a circumcenter or a barycenter for triangular grids and intersection of diagonals for quadrilateral grids. We can now summarize the most important ingredients of the 1-D proof.",
